Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
Hi! Thanks to everyone who put answered the survey I put together and to everyone who has helped me put this together! And thanks to Joe for opening the thread and providing some incentives! :)

This thread is the place to discuss and share before, during, and after the game jam proper.

Feel free to **organize teams** of up to 4 in here! Discuss your skills and game design sensibilities! Make sure that you will properly be able to work together during the week of the jam - we are a global discord, after all!
(Please DM me to let me know what times your team wants to work with so we can properly communicate with you)

During the jam, feel free to post updates, ask questions, or playtest builds! For people who skimmed the timestamps, this will be a **weeklong jam**, so keep that in mind.
(Games will be submitted through an itch.io page. I will put it up as we get closer to the date of the event. Someone on your team will need an itch.io account.)

Feel free to ping me (<@218810384344154113>) here with any questions or concerns you may have about the jam! I hope this can be an edifying experience for those who feel uncertain of their abilities, and a chance to flex a bit for those who really want to sweat for some marbles‚Ñ¢.
Ultimately, I hope it's fun for everyone who participates and for everyone in the community who will get to see some cool games!

- Best Overall (The Big Cheese)

(1 marble‚Ñ¢ to be awarded per team for each category)

Content:
just trying to avoid making the deadline be at like, 3 am for someone, and there are few enough people participating that i can handle organizing multiple windows for everyone. i *really* don't want to pressure anyone to lose sleep over this, and the timezones people were reporting were pretty widespread.

Author: dannykay1
Content:
Hello Jads,
I want to form a small team for the jam. I've participated in a few jams before with varying degrees of success. I'm a game designer and developer. I can do most stuff in **Unity** but I prefer to have talented people take over art/animation/SFX. Main goals are to **have fun, create a nice collaborative environment, and make a game!**
More info if you're interested:
- We'll be using **Unity**
- We're looking for **artists, animation/sound effects** people
- I'm in **CET** time zone.
- Bonus if you can use **Github**
- Game genre is obviously undecided, but it will probably lean into action/ exploration rather than puzzle/ visual novel.

Feel free to DM me. Please include your past experience and your availability *(are you also working full-time?)*

Content: not really

Author: marl

Author: marl

Author: marl
Content: but it keeps giving me nonsense

Author: marl
Content: I then added force_raycast_update() and it works magically

Author: zettexe2
Content: yeah it only updates once per physics frame at the start of the frame

Author: marl
Content: after an hour of googling all I've found is people going "yeah sometimes when raycast doesn't work just call force_raycast_update() ü§∑"

Author: zettexe2
Content: so it was checking the old position on the next frame over

Author: marl
Content: but why

Author: zettexe2
Content: performance

Author: zettexe2
Content: raycasts are expensive

Author: marl
Content: so even though I directly altered the position of the ray, which is confirmed by the print statement

Author: marl
Content: the collision check is actually not performed with that value?

Author: pinkhair
Content: I wish I had time/talent to write a new song

Author: zettexe2
Content: no, the collision check is performed, then you change the value, and then you check the result of the collision check

Author: marl
Content: am I not changing the value before the check?

Author: zettexe2
Content: by calling force_raycast_update it goes check collision, change value, check collision, get result of collision

Author: marl
Content: alright I am confused

Author: marl
Content: the first line changes the value for the ray, and the second line checks collision, right

Author: zettexe2
Content: no, the second line gets the result of the collision check, the collision check happened at the start of the frame

Author: marl
Content: oh

Author: marl
Content: so does it just passively do this every frame?

Author: zettexe2
Content: yeah

Content: yeah, file uploads don't lock until the jam submission period ends, so you can make a page ahead of time and add it. in fact, it's definitely not a bad idea to submit something like, a day ahead of the deadline just in case something disastrous happens. all the submissions are hidden until voting starts, so feel free to do that.

Content: so long as the music is royalty free?? idk what anime music would fit that

Author: brainlessdood
Content: So if I just download an anime op from youtube my game will be disqualified entirely?

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: it's about proportions. if you just use it for a short bit or something, then you could still be eligible. if it's the main background theme for the entire gameplay, then it wouldn't make sense for it to be in the running for best audio. also, yeah, it might not be a great idea to just use someone else's music without permission like that even though it's just a game jam game.

Author: brainlessdood
Content: I'm saying I want to use anime music even if it disqualifies me from the best audio category, as long as it doesn't disqualify me from the game jam entirely

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: being disqualified from a specific category doesn't disqualify you overall, no.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: there's a place on the submission page to indicate that you don't think your project should be eligible to be judged for its audio.

Author: brainlessdood
Content: Kk, thanks

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: i would be remiss to not mention that using copyrighted content is in the same legal grey area here that it is when posting anything on the internet. it's probably pretty unlikely that a company or rights holder would see this small game made for a relatively obscure game jam, but it would still be open to dmca issues if it somehow caught their attention. it would definitely be ideal if you could find something that sounds like an anime op with more permissive licensing, but i don't know the needs of your game.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
On that note, we are coming up on the home stretch as there will only be 2 days left in the jam once we hit noon for the UTC-8 teams.

If you weren't planning on doing so already, I **heavily** suggest making a build of your game a day ahead of the final deadline. Run it on a computer that wasn't used to develop it (if at all possible) to see if unexpected things happen. Keep it as a backup in case something happens outside of your control so you at least have *something* to submit. Consider starting to put together the itch page for your project. Uploads on itch pages shouldn't lock until the final submission deadline.

I hope your games are coming along well - even if they aren't exactly as you might have imagined them at the beginning of the week! I have been personally enjoying seeing all the sneak peeks here and there, and I can't wait to actually play them! Good luck to all the teams, and please make sure to take care of yourselves even through this last leg of the jam!

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
Okay! I have heard back from all of the UTC group teams! The game jam is currently sitting at 9 entries :)

I see some of you are already mentioning it, but please relax and take care of yourselves! Get some good rest and then face your next few days with ability to replenish the mental, emotional, and physical energy you were probably expending during the jam. There will be games to play and vote on once you are ready to come back :)

Thank you all for lending us your time, even if your submission (or lack thereof) didn't work out exactly the way you wanted it. It will be another few hours untl the UTC-8 group projects start rolling in, and then we will have a proper close to the game jamming period. Good luck to any of those still working!

Content: the messages are objects with a property which makes them "the ground". when one is created, it makes every combat component move up with it

Content: In the enchanting world of JomsQuest, the reason behind our protagonist Joms being a boy is intricately woven into the complex lore of JomsQuest. You see, JomsQuest is not your ordinary video game; it's a tapestry of myth, legend, and pixels that spans across dimensions and epochs. It all started at the end of JomsQuest III during a climactic battle with the Shadowbane, it became clear that the ancient prophecy was intricately linked to the entity's defeat. The prophecy hinted at the importance of the chosen one embracing their masculine side to unlock their full potential. This was crucial to wielding the legendary Sword of Eclipses, the only weapon capable of defeating the Shadowbane. True fans understand this and wouldn't question the deep and impactful lore within the JomsQuest franchise.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
The votes are in! The scores are tallied!
The JADS Game Jam 2023 winners are:

- Best Visuals: Discord on the Discord
- Best Audios: Soups On
- Best Use of Theme: Waiter, There's A Cat In My Soup
- Community Favorite: One Guy vs JADS
- Best Overall (The Big Cheese): One Guy vs JADS

Take a look at the Itch page if you would like to see more in-depth rankings. Winners: keep reading for marble instructions.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
All winning teams have earned one (1) anime marble‚Ñ¢ for every category that they won! If you are on a winning team, please contact me directly about your choice for your anime marbles so I can gather them all and send them all as a group to the relevant parties.

Each marble earned for a category is **shared** for the entire team! You will need to come to an agreement amongst yourselves for your picks! I **will** be checking with all team members to make sure that individual teams are in agreement before confirming the choices.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
If you have any **feedback or suggestions**, any at all, for the now previous and future possible game jams, the feedback survey is now live!

Please answer my questions and send your opinions via this link:
https://forms.gle/L1gST2Y15SFWSapL6

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
And finally, a thank you to everyone who participated in their own ways!
Thanks to Irene for helping me get the ball rolling on the event, and thanks to Snek (you know the one) & Falzar for their help running the event and managing the thread!
Thanks again, of course, to all the people here who gave their time and effort, however brief, to make games happen! A special thanks to the people who were helpful to others here and who otherwise helped to give the jam a good vibe!
Thanks to the people in JADS who played some games and maybe even voted! 214 ratings were behind whatever the Community Favorite marble ends up going towards.
And speaking of marbles, a final thanks to Joe for providing the marbles for the event! If it weren't for his ace thread-making skills, I wouldn't have anywhere to post this particular message.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: Just putting this here in this thread in case people watch the current stream VOD and wonder what came of it. Or for people who don't watch the stream and therefore aren't aware, I suppose.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content:
Tl;dr: Yes, Joe has been made aware of the jam games. He is considering whether or not he wants to play them on stream - currently leaning more likely than not. He doesn't know if he wants to do it before or after the upcoming break if he does decide to stream them.

Please don't be annoying and bug him about it to try to make sure it happens. He's already considering it, which is more than there was ever any expectation of.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: (And, if you feel uncomfortable having your game shown on stream, that is totally understandable. Feel free to DM me if you would like to opt out in case a stream does happen. It is pretty unlikely we will recommend he play any games that were submitted in a totally incomplete state.)

Author: zargy
Content: I hope he decides to do it after break, since I think there's a lot we want to do with our game. There's a lot of content we had to cut from it for the deadline.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: Also for the record, my thoughts on people making more "polished" versions of the games for stream. Obviously, if people just want to have more polished versions of their game for their own purposes, that's fine.

Author: dannykay1
Content: While I ultimately don't care and would be happy to just get them on stream, I think it's better to just show the jam version.

Author: celestinno
Content: im interested in participating on the next one, whenever that may be

Author: zargy
Content: To be clear, I'm fine if the current version gets shown, though I'd want to add some kind of text/popup to the main menu indicating that it isn't a final product and has a few issues that we weren't able to solve due to lack of time. I think that's fair and I think everybody should be allowed to do that with their games if they personally feel like that's the case.

Author: zerstorenhv
Content: That's kind of inherent with it being a game jam game. I'm sure "this was made in just 7 days" would be said plenty of times throughout.
